  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 태뢰(太牢) : '
    value: 제사 지낼 때에 큰 소를 잡는 것을 말한다.
english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Four Satisfactions
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In years past, my father established a retreat beyond the western gates of the city. The valleys ran deep and secluded, the landscape remote and tranquil—as if another world had been fashioned there. Truly a place of delight. When it came into my possession, I would visit often, making it my sanctuary for reading and quiet contemplation. There was land to till and eat from. There were mulberry trees to raise silkworms and weave cloth. There was spring water to drink. There was wood to gather for fuel. Four things aligned with my desire—and so I named the hall "Four Satisfactions."

    And yet, consider those whose wealth runs deep and rank sits heavy upon them—who ride the wind of authority and grasp at power. All that they desire comes readily to hand. But I? Already worn by hardship, I have spent a lifetime with scarcely one thing to call my own. Now, suddenly, I possess these four. How presumptuous it seems. Yet remember: the grandest sacrificial feast begins with humble broth. The thousand-league journey starts at the door. All things proceed by gradual measure.

    Should I dwell in this hall and truly taste the joys of field and garden, then perhaps I might spit out the tangled threads of the world, dust off my robes, bind my feet, and return to the old gardens to grow old. There I would become an ancient farmer of the great peace—striking the earth and drumming my belly, singing praises of the sage's way, letting the melodies flow through pipes and strings. What then could not be satisfied?

    Once, within these halls, I composed three poems, which appear in my collection under the title "Poems of the Western Suburb Thatched Hall." One verse reads:

    How delightful the joys of the farming life—
    From this day forth begins the homecoming to the fields.

    This alone captures my true desire. On this day, the Clouded Hermit sets down this record.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The ''Four Satisfactions'' refers to the four basic provisions the poet found sufficient for life: cultivated fields, mulberry trees for sericulture, spring water, and firewood. These represent the poet''s embrace of simple, rural contentment.'
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'grand sacrificial feast' (太牢) alludes to the Confucian principle that great things grow from humble beginnings—a classical expression of patience and gradual progress.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Clouded Hermit' (白雲居士) was Lee Gyubo's chosen pen name, expressing his aspiration toward reclusive simplicity.
